rogram (FDLP).  aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF caption (DNI, viewed March 10, 2026). 0aPolitical violencezSahel. 0aTerrorismzSahel.40uhttps://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo253713704 uhttps://www.dni.gov/files/ODNI/documents/assessments/NICM-Declassified-Sahelian-Instability-Spreading-Sept2024.pdf  aC0bGPO  abc87 20260310b20260310  aUNREPORTEDPUBSASKGPOb20260310  abc87 2026052804818cam a2200577 i 00146916220260507115511.0m     o  d f      cr |||||||||||260313s2026    oruab   ob   f000 0 eng c  a(OCoLC)1579146644  aGPObengerdaepncGPOdAGMdOCLCOdGPO  apcc  an-us-ak  aGPOO  a0083-B-06 (online)0 aA 13.88:PNW-GTR-10401 aD'Amore, David V.,eauthor.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/no201118204010aDecision support for managing mixed species riparian forests in southeast Alaska /cDavid V. D'Amore [and three others]. 1aPortland, OR :bForest Service, U.S. Department of Agriculture, Pacific Northwest Research Station,c2026.  a1 online resource (32 pages) :bcolor illustrations, color map.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aGeneral Technical Report ;vPNW-GTR-1040  a"March 2026."  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 14-17).  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds.  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP).3 a"Riparian zones are important ecotones, integrating terrestrial and aquatic functions that support ecosystem productivity. A key ecological role of riparian zones is the production of large conifers that eventually enter the stream and provide important habitat complexity within the freshwater ecosystem. Many riparian zones in south-east Alaska were heavily disturbed during logging operations from 1950 to 1980, which depleted the large wood supply to streams. Abundant conifer and red alder regeneration was common after harvest, replenishing a young population of trees, but the presence of red alder has been perceived to inhibit conifer stand development and large wood recruitment to streams.^Therefore, alder thinning has been used to accelerate conifer growth and address the large wood deficit in streams.^However, the trajectory of stand growth in these mixed species riparian stands is complex, and the response to alder or conifer thinning has not been thoroughly documented since riparian restoration projects have been implemented throughout southeast Alaska. Further, few protocols exist for evaluating the progress and success of restoration actions. To address this need, we measured species abundance, tree density, light, and growth history on dominant landforms associated with varying stream geomorphological classes in 13 postharvest riparian stands. The presence of alder did not negatively affect conifer growth across a range of stand and landform conditions. Thinning conifers on terrace landforms increased the annual stand growth increment where conifers dominated.^In the absence of thinning, equal stocking of alder and coni-fer did not affect conifer growth increment on terraces in mixed stands.^We found that the density to tree size ratio (trees per hectare to quadratic mean diameter) is a useful metric to monitor the progress of stands toward desired late-seral conditions. These results indicate that mixed species stands do not impede conifer growth and provide valuable riparian nutrient inputs, improved light, and biological diversity."  aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF cover (FS, viewed March 13, 2026). 0aRiparian forestszAlaska. 0aRiparian restorationzAlaska. 0aStream restorationzAlaska. 0aForest resiliencezAlaska. 0aSilvicultural systemszAlaska. 0aForest ecologyxResearchzAlaska. 0aConifersxResearchzAlaska. 0aAlderxResearchzAlaska. 7aTechnical reports.2lcgft0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/genreForms/gf20150260932 aPacific Northwest Research Station (Portland, Or.),eissuing body.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n8530339908iPrint version:aD'Amore, David V.tDecision support for managing mixed species riparian forests in southeast Alaskaw(OCoLC)1588976338 0aGeneral technical report PNW ;vPNW-GTR-1040.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n8471178840uhttps://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo253889704 zAddress at time of PURL creationuhttps://research.fs.usda.gov/download/treesearch/80217.pdf  aC0bGPO  abcs87 20260313b20260313  aUNREPORTEDPUBSSTAFFb20260313  aCATLEVELBASICb20260313  abc48 20260507  aVEND01b2026052902537cam a2200541 i 00146965320260529115514.0m     o  d f      cr |||||||||||250924s2025    dcu     ob   f000 0 eng c8 a59-006q(GPO jacket number)  a(OCoLC)1539319340  aGPObengerdaepncGPOdGPO  apcc  an-us---  aDGPO  a1008-I (online)0 aY 1.1/8:119-2381 aUnited States.bCongress.bHouse.bCommittee on Transportation and Infrastructure,eauthor.10aShared Property Agency Collaboration and Engagement Act of 2025 :breport (to accompany H.R. 3424), (including cost estimate of the Congressional Budget Office). 1a[Washington, D.C.] :b[U.S. Government Publishing Office],c[2025]  a1 online resource (7 pages).  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aReport / 119th Congress, 1st session, House of Representatives ;v119-238  aAccess ID (govinfo): CRPT-119hrpt238.  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds.  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP).  a"September 8, 2025."  aReferred bill: H.R. 3424.  aIncludes bibliographical references.  aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF caption (GovInfo, viewed September 24, 2025). 0aPublic buildingszUn