 before the Committee on Foreign Affairs, U.S. House of Representatives, One Hundred Eighteenth Congress, second session, September 18, 2024. 1aWashington :bU.S. Government Publishing Office,c2026.  a1 online resource (iii,70 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds.  aAssociated bill citation(s): H. Res. 837; H.R. 8361; H.R. 8892.  a"Serial no. 118-131."  aIncludes bibliographical references.0 aHearing witnesses: Statement of Kurt Campbell, Deputy Secretary, Department of State.  aDate of hearing: 2024-09-18.  aDescription based on online resource, PDF version; title from title page (GovInfo, viewed May 18, 2026).  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP). 0aChinaxTerritorial expansion. 0aSouth China SeaxStrategic aspects. 0aIndo-Pacific RegionxStrategic aspects. 0aNational securityzUnited States. 0aChinaxForeign relationszUnited States. 0aUnited StatesxForeign relationszChina. 7aInternational Affairs.2cgpa 7aLegislative hearings.2lcgft08iPrint version:aUnited States. Congress. House. Committee on Foreign Affairs.tGreat power competition in the indo-pacificw(OCoLC)159183115040uhttps://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo256131704 zAddress at time of PURL creationuhttps://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/CHRG-118hhrg63340/pdf/CHRG-118hhrg63340.pdf  aC0bGPO  abca68 20260518b2026051804275cam a2200541 i 00147294320260518125234.0m     o  d f      161027e201610  dcua    ob   f000 0 eng c  a(OCoLC)961278056  aSTFbengerdaepncSTFdOCLCOdOCLCFdOCLCOdOCLCLdGPO  apcc  an-us---  aXZL4 4aKF3155  a0535 (online)0 aFT 1.2:P 27/200aPatent assertion entity activity :ban FTC study /ca report of the Federal Trade Commission. 1a[Washington, D.C.] :bFederal Trade Commission,cOctober 2016.  a1 online resource (269 pages in various pagings) :bcolor illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext file2rda  a"October 2016"--Cover.  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds.  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP).  aIncludes bibliographical references.  aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (FTC, viewed October 27, 2016).  a"The report examines non-public information and data covering the period 2009 to 2014 from 22 PAEs, 327 PAE affiliates, and more than 2100 holding entities (those entities that did not assert patents) obtained through compulsory process orders (subpoenas) using the agency's authority under Section 6(b) of the FTC Act. The report found two types of PAEs that use distinctly different business models. One type, referred to in the report as Portfolio PAEs, were strongly capitalized and purchased patents outright. They negotiated broad licenses, covering large patent portfolios, frequently worth more than $1 million. The second, more common, type, referred to in the report as Litigation PAEs, frequently relied on revenue sharing agreements to acquire patents. They overwhelmingly filed infringement lawsuits before securing licenses, which covered a small number of patents and were generally less valuable. The report found that, among the PAEs in the study, Litigation PAEs accounted for 96 percent of all patent infringement lawsuits, but generated only about 20 percent of all reported PAE revenues. The report also found that 93 percent of the patent licensing agreements held by Litigation PAEs resulted from litigation, while for Portfolio PAEs that figure was 29 percent. The study found that the royalties typically yielded by Litigation PAE licenses were less than the lower bounds of early stage litigation costs. This data is consistent with nuisance litigation, in which defendant companies decide to settle based on the cost of litigation rather than the likelihood of their infringement."--FTC press release. 0aPatent infringementzUnited States. 0aPatent suitszUnited States. 0aPatent laws and legislationzUnited States. 6aBrevets d'invention0(CaQQLa)201-0288198xContrefaçon0(CaQQLa)201-0288198zÉtats-Unis.0(CaQQLa)201-0407727 6aActions en contrefaçon0(CaQQLa)201-0078042zÉtats-Unis.0(CaQQLa)201-0407727 7aPatent infringement.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01054821 7aPatent laws and legislation.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01054823 7aPatent suits.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01054860 7aUnited States.2fast0(OCoLC)fst012041551https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PBJtxgQXMWqmjMjjwXRHgrq1 aUnited States.bFederal Trade Commission,eissuing body.08iPrint version:tPatent assertion entity activity.w(OCoLC)96233037040uhttps://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo248256704 zAddress at time of PURL creation:uhttps://www.ftc.gov/system/files/documents/reports/patent-assertion-entity-activity-ftc-study/p131203_patent_assertion_entity_activity_an_ftc_study_0.pdf4 uhttps://purl.stanford.edu/pm912cz2709  aC0bGPO  abc109 20260518b20260518  aBIBCONEWb20260518  aUNREPORTEDPUBSSTAFFb2026051802067cam a2200433 i 00147294420260518125856.0m     o  d f      240126s2024    aluab   ob   f000 0 eng d  a(OCoLC)1419000896  aAAUbengerdaepncAAUdOCLCOdOCLCQdAAUdOCLCLdOCLCOdGPO  aa-cc---ae-ru---  aXZL4  a0422-K (online)0 aD 301.26/6:N 88/41 aShats, Daniel,eauthor.10aChina-Russia nuclear industry cooperation /cDaniel Shats ; prepared by BluePath Labs. 1aMontgomery, AL :bChina Aerospace Studies Institute,c2024.  a1 online resource (39 pages) :billustrations, map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atextbPDF2rdaft  a"January 2024."  aThis is a pu